[SPEAKER_00]: Enhancing trade and investment opportunities.

8
00:00:55,540 --> 00:00:58,082
[SPEAKER_00]: Designing stronger education and skills policies.

9
00:00:58,834 --> 00:01:02,235
[SPEAKER_00]: and mobilizing higher levels of financing for development.

10
00:01:04,075 --> 00:01:05,816
[SPEAKER_00]: First, on trade and investment.

11
00:01:07,076 --> 00:01:19,060
[SPEAKER_00]: Africa needs simpler rules, faster border procedures, and greater data transparency in order to trade more and attract higher levels of quality investment.

12
00:01:20,260 --> 00:01:27,382
[SPEAKER_00]: Even modest improvements in trade facilitation can significantly expand export markets and reduce trade costs.

13
00:01:28,790 --> 00:01:34,814
[SPEAKER_00]: Reforms would also allow Africa to seize the potential of the massive expansion of digital trade around the world.

14
00:01:35,855 --> 00:01:41,138
[SPEAKER_00]: Barriers to digital trade in Africa decreased to some extent between 2014 and 2025.

15
00:01:41,178 --> 00:01:50,505
[SPEAKER_00]: For example, Uganda's 2019 reforms opened its telecom market by strengthening competition and introducing new licensing rules.

16
00:01:51,085 --> 00:01:56,389
[SPEAKER_00]: And last year, South Africa introduced digital license applications for key professional services.

17
00:01:57,589 --> 00:01:58,330
[SPEAKER_00]: The challenges

18
00:01:58,710 --> 00:02:03,053
[SPEAKER_00]: to build and accelerate this reform momentum right across Africa.

19
00:02:04,635 --> 00:02:07,097
[SPEAKER_00]: Second, skills and education.

20
00:02:08,198 --> 00:02:19,347
[SPEAKER_00]: Between 2020 and 2040, the number of young Africans completing secondary or higher education will more than double from 103 to 240 million young people.

21
00:02:20,527 --> 00:02:23,610
[SPEAKER_00]: This is a genuinely historic opportunity.

22
00:02:24,630 --> 00:02:32,777
[SPEAKER_00]: but it will only translate into better jobs and productivity gains if education systems successfully equip the future workforce with the right skills.

23
00:02:33,838 --> 00:02:43,446
[SPEAKER_00]: The OECD's Programme for International Student Assessment helps countries design impactful reforms to boost the quality of education systems around the world.

24
00:02:43,466 --> 00:02:48,209
[SPEAKER_00]: Morocco was the first African country to join this programme in 2018.

25
00:02:48,250 --> 00:02:53,654
[SPEAKER_00]: The 2025 edition of PISA will expand the coverage to Egypt, Kenya, Mauritius and Rwanda.

26
00:02:54,602 --> 00:02:56,723
[SPEAKER_00]: We invite others to consider joining.

27
00:02:58,084 --> 00:03:00,926
[SPEAKER_00]: Third, private finance for development.

28
00:03:02,087 --> 00:03:15,875
[SPEAKER_00]: Bilateral official development assistance from OECD Development Assistance Committee members to African countries dropped by 24% in real terms, from $36.4 billion U.S. in 24 to $27.7 billion U.S. in 25, the sharpest annual decline since 2007.

29
00:03:21,518 --> 00:03:28,620
[SPEAKER_00]: Larger and more efficient domestic capital markets in Africa could play a key role in cushioning the impact of shrinking development-wide budgets.

30
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:39,203
[SPEAKER_00]: Our OECD Africa Capital Markets Report last year showed that most debt and equity activity on the continent is concentrated in just a few countries.

31
00:03:40,003 --> 00:03:49,386
[SPEAKER_00]: Egypt, Mauritius, Nigeria, and South Africa, among the four of them, across the four of them, accounted for 61% of the continent's total outstanding corporate debt in 2024.

32
00:03:51,186 --> 00:04:03,294
[SPEAKER_00]: Encouraging cross-listing on multiple exchanges in the region and harmonizing debt market infrastructure could boost regional integration and promote capital market growth through economies of scale.

33
00:04:03,554 --> 00:04:11,119
[SPEAKER_00]: The OECD is expanding our engagement with African countries right across the continent.

34
00:04:12,220 --> 00:04:17,424
[SPEAKER_00]: OECD ministers welcomed the progress towards an enhanced partnership with Africa last month.

35
00:04:17,864 --> 00:04:20,586
[SPEAKER_00]: We will soon begin consultations on this partnership

36
00:04:21,078 --> 00:04:24,961
[SPEAKER_00]: with the African Union Commission, regional organizations and partner countries.

37
00:04:25,762 --> 00:04:35,150
[SPEAKER_00]: And later this month, we're launching the African Virtual Investment Platform with 15 pilot countries to help African countries attract more and higher quality investment.

38
00:04:36,511 --> 00:04:41,876
[SPEAKER_00]: We very much look forward to expanding this platform in the years to come to countries right across the continent.

39
00:04:43,257 --> 00:04:48,722
[SPEAKER_00]: In closing, African countries are making remarkable progress on all fronts.

40
00:04:49,750 --> 00:05:01,558
[SPEAKER_00]: Barriers to trade are lower, access to education is expanding, companies are attracting more capital, and the OECD has been proud to stand alongside Africa on this journey.

41
00:05:02,398 --> 00:05:06,741
[SPEAKER_00]: We will remain your trusted partner as we push this transformation further.

42
00:05:06,761 --> 00:05:08,002
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

